    // E.g., n=4, K = ceil(2/2) = 1.
    // E.g., n=5, K = ceil(3/2) = 2.
    // E.g., n=6, K = ceil(4/2) = 2.
    // E.g., n=7, K = ceil(5/2) = 3.

    // Since we are minimizing cost for a fixed maximum number of peaks, we should try to achieve the maximum possible number of peaks, $K$.

    const K_max = Math.ceil((n - 2) / 2);

    // We must calculate the minimum cost to achieve K_max peaks.
    // Due to the nature of the problem (only increasing values), the relative order of the chosen peaks
    // must be maintained or made strictly increasing/decreasing around the valleys.

