        // Peak at 1 needs: nums[1] > nums[0] and nums[1] > nums[2]. Cost = max(0, nums[0] + 1 - nums[1], nums[2] + 1 - nums[1])
        // Peak at 3 needs: nums[3] > nums[2] and nums[3] > nums[4]. 
        // If we increase nums[1], it affects nums[2] indirectly if nums[2] is a peak, but here nums[2] is a valley.

        // Since we are only increasing peaks, and neighbors are valleys, the neighbors' values are fixed by the original array (unless they are peaks themselves).
        // In the K_max configuration, all neighbors of peaks are valleys or boundaries, so their initial values are fixed.

        // The required value for peak $i$ is $V_i = \max(currentNums[i-1] + 1, currentNums[i+1] + 1)$.
        // The cost for peak $i$ is $\max(0, V_i - nums[i])$.

